{"question": "How is Merge Sort implemented?", "answer": "Divide and conquer sorting algorithm.", "code": {"c": "void merge(int a[], int l, int m, int r) { /* Merging logic */ }
void mergeSort(int a[], int l, int r) {
    if(l<r) { int m = l+(r-l)/2; mergeSort(a, l, m); mergeSort(a, m+1, r); merge(a, l, m, r); }
}", "cpp": "std::stable_sort(v.begin(), v.end());", "python": "def merge_sort(arr):
    if len(arr)>1:
        mid = len(arr)//2
        L, R = arr[:mid], arr[mid:]
        merge_sort(L); merge_sort(R)
        # Merge logic..."}, "explanation": "Merge Sort is a stable, divide-and-conquer sorting algorithm. It recursively splits the array into halves until single elements remain, then merges them back in sorted order. It guarantees O(n log n) time complexity in all cases, making it highly reliable for large datasets. However, it requires O(n) auxiliary space for the merging process. It is preferred for linked list sorting due to its sequential access patterns.", "language": "C / C++ / Python"}

{"question": "How is Dijkstra implemented?", "answer": "Shortest path in weighted graph.", "code": {"c": "void dijkstra(int graph[V][V], int src) { /* Priority queue implementation required in C */ }", "cpp": "#include <set>
void dijkstra(int s) { std::set<std::pair<int, int>> pq; pq.insert({0, s}); }", "python": "import heapq
def dijkstra(graph, start):
    pq = [(0, start)]
    while pq: (dist, u) = heapq.heappop(pq)"}, "explanation": "Dijkstra's Algorithm finds the shortest path from a single source vertex to all other vertices in a weighted graph with non-negative edge weights. It uses a Greedy approach, maintaining a set of shortest-reach distances and a priority queue to pick the closest unvisited node. Its complexity is O((V+E) log V) with a binary heap. It is widely used in network routing and GPS navigation systems. Note: It fails on graphs with negative weights.", "language": "C / C++ / Python"}

{"question": "How is Quick Sort implemented?", "answer": "Pivot-based partitioning sort.", "code": {"c": "int partition(int a[], int l, int h) { int p = a[h], i = (l-1); /* Swap logic */ }
void quickSort(int a[], int l, int h) {
    if(l<h) { int pi = partition(a, l, h); quickSort(a, l, pi-1); quickSort(a, pi+1, h); }
}", "cpp": "#include <algorithm>
void qsort(std::vector<int>& v) { std::sort(v.begin(), v.end()); }", "python": "def quicksort(arr):
    if len(arr) <= 1: return arr
    pivot = arr[len(arr)//2]
    left = [x for x in arr if x < pivot]
    # middle & right..."}, "explanation": "Quick Sort is a highly efficient, in-place sorting algorithm based on the divide-and-conquer principle. It selects a 'pivot' element and partitions the array such that elements smaller than the pivot are on the left and larger on the right. It then recursively sorts the sub-arrays. While its worst-case is O(n²), its average-case is O(n log n) with a very small constant factor, often outperforming Merge Sort in practice. Randomized pivot selection is commonly used to avoid the worst-case scenario.", "language": "C / C++ / Python"}

{"question": "How is Stack implemented?", "answer": "LIFO linear data structure.", "code": {"c": "#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 100
int stack[MAX], top = -1;
void push(int x) { if(top < MAX-1) stack[++top] = x; }
int pop() { return (top >= 0) ? stack[top--] : -1; }
int main() { push(10); printf("%d", pop()); return 0; }", "cpp": "#include <iostream>
#include <stack>
int main() { std::stack<int> s; s.push(10); std::cout << s.top(); s.pop(); return 0; }", "python": "class Stack:
    def __init__(self): self.items = []
    def push(self, x): self.items.append(x)
    def pop(self): return self.items.pop() if self.items else None
s = Stack(); s.push(10); print(s.pop())"}, "explanation": "A Stack is a fundamental LIFO (Last-In, First-Out) data structure. It mimics a physical stack of plates where elements are added (Push) and removed (Pop) only from the Top. Internally, it can be implemented using arrays or linked lists. It is crucial for expression parsing, depth-first search, and managing function calls in the OS kernel. Key operations take O(1) time. Overflow occurs when the fixed size is exceeded, while Underflow happens on pop from an empty stack.", "language": "C / C++ / Python"}

{"question": "How is Graph implemented?", "answer": "Nodes and edges representing relations.", "code": {"c": "#include <stdio.h>
int adj[10][10], visited[10];
void dfs(int u, int n) {
    visited[u] = 1; printf("%d ", u);
    for(int v=0; v<n; v++) if(adj[u][v] && !visited[v]) dfs(v, n);
}", "cpp": "#include <vector>
#include <queue>
void bfs(int s, std::vector<int> adj[]) {
    std::queue<int> q; q.push(s); 
}", "python": "def dfs(u, graph, visited):
    visited.add(u)
    for v in graph[u]:
        if v not in visited: dfs(v, graph, visited)"}, "explanation": "Graphs represent relationships between objects (Nodes) via Edges. They can be Directed (one-way) or Undirected (mutual). Traversal is performed using Breadth-First Search (BFS) for layer-by-layer exploration or Depth-First Search (DFS) for path-based deep dives. BFS uses a Queue and is ideal for finding shortest paths in unweighted graphs, while DFS uses a Stack (or recursion) and is used for topological sorting or cycle detection. Complexity depends on V (vertices) and E (edges), typically O(V+E).", "language": "C / C++ / Python"}

