{"question": "How is Linked List implemented?", "answer": "Chain of nodes with pointers.", "code": {"c": "#include <stdlib.h>
struct Node { int data; struct Node *next; };
void insert(struct Node** head, int x) {
    struct Node* n = malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    n->data = x; n->next = *head; *head = n;
}", "cpp": "struct Node { int data; Node* next; };", "python": "class Node:
    def __init__(self, data): self.data = data; self.next = None"}, "explanation": "Linked Lists are dynamic data structures consisting of nodes, where each node contains data and a pointer to the next node. Unlike arrays, they don't require contiguous memory and can grow/shrink easily. Operations like insertion and deletion at the head are O(1), but searching takes O(n). Types include Singly, Doubly (pointers in both directions), and Circular (last node points to first). Memory management is critical to avoid leaks.", "language": "C / C++ / Python"}

