{"question": "How is Queue implemented?", "answer": "FIFO linear data structure.", "code": {"c": "#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 5
int q[MAX], f=-1, r=-1;
void enq(int x) { if((r+1)%MAX != f) { if(f==-1)f=0; r=(r+1)%MAX; q[r]=x; } }
int deq() { if(f==-1) return -1; int x=q[f]; if(f==r) f=r=-1; else f=(f+1)%MAX; return x; }", "cpp": "#include <iostream>
#include <queue>
int main() { std::queue<int> q; q.push(1); q.pop(); return 0; }", "python": "from collections import deque
q = deque()
q.append(1) # Enqueue
q.popleft() # Dequeue"}, "explanation": "A Queue follows the FIFO (First-In, First-Out) principle, where insertion happens at the Rear and deletion at the Front. It is essential for asynchronous data transfers, task scheduling, and breadth-first search. Common variations include Circular Queues, Priority Queues, and Deques. In a Circular Queue, the last position is connected back to the first to optimize memory utilization. Complexity for enqueue and dequeue is typically O(1).", "language": "C / C++ / Python"}

