{"question": "How is Stack implemented?", "answer": "LIFO linear data structure.", "code": {"c": "#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 100
int stack[MAX], top = -1;
void push(int x) { if(top < MAX-1) stack[++top] = x; }
int pop() { return (top >= 0) ? stack[top--] : -1; }
int main() { push(10); printf("%d", pop()); return 0; }", "cpp": "#include <iostream>
#include <stack>
int main() { std::stack<int> s; s.push(10); std::cout << s.top(); s.pop(); return 0; }", "python": "class Stack:
    def __init__(self): self.items = []
    def push(self, x): self.items.append(x)
    def pop(self): return self.items.pop() if self.items else None
s = Stack(); s.push(10); print(s.pop())"}, "explanation": "A Stack is a fundamental LIFO (Last-In, First-Out) data structure. It mimics a physical stack of plates where elements are added (Push) and removed (Pop) only from the Top. Internally, it can be implemented using arrays or linked lists. It is crucial for expression parsing, depth-first search, and managing function calls in the OS kernel. Key operations take O(1) time. Overflow occurs when the fixed size is exceeded, while Underflow happens on pop from an empty stack.", "language": "C / C++ / Python"}

