        root = left_rotate(root)
    return root"}, "execution_steps": ["1. Standard BST search for key.", "2. Perform zig (single rotation) or zig-zig/zig-zag (double rotation) based on parent-grandparent alignment.", "3. Accessed node becomes the new root."], "variants": ["AVL Tree", "Red-Black Tree"], "visual_hooks": ["animate_splay_rotation(key)", "highlight_root_change(node)"], "reasoning_map": {"problem": "Standard BSTs have no access-pattern optimization.", "solution": "Splay accessed node to root for faster future access.", "tradeoffs": "Amortized-efficient but individual operations can be O(n) in worst case."}}

{"title": "B-Tree", "summary": "A self-balancing multi-way search tree designed for disk storage, where each node holds multiple keys and children to minimize I/O operations.", "key_points": ["Each node can have up to 2t-1 keys (t = minimum degree).", "All leaves are at the same depth.", "Ideal for databases and file systems."], "code": {"python": "class BTreeNode:
