{"title": "Shell Sort", "summary": "An in-place comparison sort that generalizes insertion sort by first sorting elements far apart, then reducing the gap progressively.", "key_points": ["Gap sequence selection affects performance significantly.", "Better than Insertion Sort for medium-sized arrays.", "Not stable by default."], "code": {"c": "void shellSort(int arr[], int n) {
    for (int gap = n/2; gap > 0; gap /= 2)
        for (int i = gap; i < n; i++) {
            int temp = arr[i], j;
            for (j = i; j >= gap && arr[j-gap] > temp; j -= gap)
                arr[j] = arr[j-gap];
            arr[j] = temp;
        }
}", "python": "def shell_sort(arr):
    n = len(arr)
    gap = n // 2
    while gap > 0:
        for i in range(gap, n):
            temp = arr[i]
            j = i
            while j >= gap and arr[j - gap] > temp:
                arr[j] = arr[j - gap]
                j -= gap
            arr[j] = temp
        gap //= 2
    return arr"}, "execution_steps": ["1. Start with gap = n/2.", "2. Perform insertion sort for elements 'gap' apart.", "3. Reduce gap by half each iteration.", "4. Repeat until gap = 1 (final insertion sort pass)."], "variants": ["Insertion Sort", "Bubble Sort"], "visual_hooks": ["animate_gap_reduction(gap)", "highlight_gap_groups(gap, arr)"], "reasoning_map": {"problem": "Insertion sort is O(n^2) due to adjacent swaps only.", "solution": "First sort elements far apart to reduce large inversions quickly.", "tradeoffs": "Better than O(n^2) average but complex gap analysis; not stable."}}

{"title": "Heap Sort", "summary": "A comparison-based sorting algorithm that uses a max-heap to repeatedly extract the maximum element and build a sorted array.", "key_points": ["O(n log n) guaranteed time complexity.", "In-place sorting; O(1) extra space.", "Not stable."], "code": {"c": "void heapify(int arr[], int n, int i) {
    int largest = i, l = 2*i+1, r = 2*i+2;
    if (l < n && arr[l] > arr[largest]) largest = l;
    if (r < n && arr[r] > arr[largest]) largest = r;
    if (largest != i) { swap(&arr[i], &arr[largest]); heapify(arr, n, largest); }
}
void heapSort(int arr[], int n) {
    for (int i = n/2-1; i >= 0; i--) heapify(arr, n, i);
    for (int i = n-1; i > 0; i--) { swap(&arr[0], &arr[i]); heapify(arr, i, 0); }
}", "python": "import heapq
def heap_sort(arr):
    heapq.heapify(arr)
    return [heapq.heappop(arr) for _ in range(len(arr))]"}, "execution_steps": ["1. Build a max-heap from the input array (O(n)).", "2. Swap root (max) with the last element.", "3. Reduce heap size by 1 and heapify from root.", "4. Repeat step 2-3 until heap size is 1."], "variants": ["Merge Sort", "Quick Sort"], "visual_hooks": ["animate_heapify(root, n)", "highlight_max_extraction(root)"], "reasoning_map": {"problem": "Need guaranteed O(n log n) with O(1) space (unlike Merge Sort).", "solution": "Exploit max-heap property to extract sorted elements.", "tradeoffs": "Guaranteed O(n log n) and O(1) space but poor cache locality; outperformed by Quick Sort in practice."}}

{"title": "DFS (Depth First Search)", "summary": "A graph traversal algorithm that explores as far as possible along each branch before backtracking, using a stack (or recursion).", "key_points": ["Uses stack (explicit or call stack) for traversal.", "Time complexity O(V + E).", "Used for topological sort, cycle detection, connected components."], "code": {"c": "void dfs(int graph[][V], int visited[], int v) {
