{"title": "Infix to Postfix Conversion", "summary": "Converts a standard infix expression (e.g., A+B*C) to postfix (e.g., ABC*+) using a stack to respect operator precedence without parentheses.", "key_points": ["Postfix (RPN) eliminates need for parentheses.", "Operator stack is used to hold pending operators by precedence.", "Foundation for expression tree building and compiler design."], "code": {"python": "def infix_to_postfix(expr):
    prec = {'+': 1, '-': 1, '*': 2, '/': 2, '^': 3}
    stack, output = [], []
    for ch in expr:
        if ch.isalnum():
            output.append(ch)
        elif ch == '(':
            stack.append(ch)
        elif ch == ')':
            while stack and stack[-1] != '(':
                output.append(stack.pop())
            stack.pop()
        else:
            while stack and stack[-1] != '(' and prec.get(stack[-1], 0) >= prec.get(ch, 0):
                output.append(stack.pop())
            stack.append(ch)
    while stack:
        output.append(stack.pop())
    return ''.join(output)"}, "execution_steps": ["1. Scan expression left to right.", "2. Operand → add to output.", "3. '(' → push to stack. ')' → pop stack to output until '('.", "4. Operator → pop higher/equal precedence ops from stack, then push.", "5. End: pop all remaining ops from stack to output."], "variants": ["Postfix Evaluation", "Expression Tree"], "visual_hooks": ["animate_operator_push(op)", "show_precedence_comparison(op1, op2)"], "reasoning_map": {"problem": "Evaluating infix expressions requires tracking parentheses and precedence.", "solution": "Convert to postfix so evaluation is a simple left-to-right stack scan.", "tradeoffs": "O(n) conversion; postfix evaluation is simpler and ideal for stack-based VMs."}}

{"title": "Postfix Evaluation", "summary": "Evaluates a postfix (Reverse Polish Notation) expression by scanning left to right, pushing operands and applying operators to the top two stack elements.", "key_points": ["No parentheses or precedence rules needed.", "O(n) time complexity.", "Used in stack-based calculators and virtual machines."], "code": {"python": "def eval_postfix(expr):
    stack = []
    for token in expr.split():
        if token.lstrip('-').isdigit():
            stack.append(int(token))
        else:
            b, a = stack.pop(), stack.pop()
            if token == '+': stack.append(a + b)
            elif token == '-': stack.append(a - b)
            elif token == '*': stack.append(a * b)
            elif token == '/': stack.append(int(a / b))
    return stack[0]"}, "execution_steps": ["1. Scan postfix expression left to right.", "2. Operand → push to stack.", "3. Operator → pop two operands, apply operator, push result.", "4. Final stack item is the result."], "variants": ["Infix to Postfix Conversion", "Expression Tree"], "visual_hooks": ["animate_stack_push(operand)", "animate_stack_pop_apply(op)"], "reasoning_map": {"problem": "Infix expressions are hard to evaluate directly.", "solution": "Evaluate postfix using simple stack push/pop operations.", "tradeoffs": "Linearly efficient; used in bytecode interpreters and scientific calculators."}}

{"title": "Adjacency Matrix", "summary": "A 2D matrix representation of a graph where matrix[i][j] = 1 if there is an edge from vertex i to vertex j.", "key_points": ["O(1) edge lookup but O(V^2) space.", "Best for dense graphs.", "Simple to implement and understand."], "code": {"c": "int matrix[5][5] = {0};
