{"title": "Stack", "summary": "A linear LIFO (Last-In, First-Out) data structure where elements are inserted and removed only from one end called the top. Used in function call management, expression evaluation, and backtracking.", "key_points": ["LIFO order: last element pushed is first element popped.", "Core operations: push (top), pop (top), peek. All O(1).", "Stack overflow: push on full stack. Stack underflow: pop from empty stack.", "Used in recursion call stack, undo operations, DFS, and syntax parsing."], "code": {"c": "#define MAX 100
int stack[MAX], top = -1;

void push(int val) {
    if (top == MAX - 1) { printf("Overflow\n"); return; }
    stack[++top] = val;
}

int pop() {
    if (top == -1) { printf("Underflow\n"); return -1; }
    return stack[top--];
}

int peek() { return (top == -1) ? -1 : stack[top]; }", "python": "class Stack:
    def __init__(self):
        self.items = []

    def push(self, val):
        self.items.append(val)

    def pop(self):
