{"title": "Linked List", "summary": "A dynamic linear data structure of nodes where each node stores data and a pointer to the next node. Unlike arrays, it allocates memory at runtime enabling efficient insertions and deletions.", "key_points": ["Dynamic memory allocation — no pre-defined size.", "O(1) insertion/deletion at head. O(n) at arbitrary positions.", "O(n) search — no random access like arrays.", "Types: Singly, Doubly, Circular Linked List.", "Used in implementing stacks, queues, adjacency lists."], "code": {"c": "struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node* next;
};

void insertFront(struct Node **head, int val) {
    struct Node* n = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    n->data = val;
    n->next = *head;
    *head = n;
}

void printList(struct Node* head) {
    while (head) {
        printf("%d -> ", head->data);
        head = head->next;
    }
    printf("NULL\n");
}", "python": "class Node:
    def __init__(self, val):
        self.val = val
        self.next = None

class LinkedList:
    def __init__(self):
        self.head = None

    def insert_front(self, val):
        node = Node(val)
        node.next = self.head
        self.head = node

    def display(self):
        cur = self.head
        while cur:
            print(cur.val, end=' -> ')
            cur = cur.next
        print('NULL')

ll = LinkedList()
ll.insert_front(10)
ll.insert_front(20)
ll.display()  # 20 -> 10 -> NULL"}, "execution_steps": ["1. Create head pointer, initialized to NULL.", "2. insertFront: create node, set node->next = head, update head = node.", "3. insertEnd: traverse to last node, set last->next = new node.", "4. delete: find predecessor, set pred->next = target->next, free target.", "5. search: traverse linearly comparing data."], "variants": ["Doubly Linked List", "Circular Linked List", "Array"], "visual_hooks": ["animate_node_link(node, next)", "animate_insert_front(val)", "show_head_pointer()"], "reasoning_map": {"problem": "Arrays have fixed size and O(n) insertion/deletion cost.", "solution": "Link nodes via pointers for O(1) head insertion and dynamic sizing.", "tradeoffs": "No random access; uses extra pointer memory; poor cache locality vs arrays."}}

{"title": "Recursion", "summary": "A programming technique where a function calls itself to solve a smaller instance of the same problem, relying on a base case to terminate. Fundamental to divide-and-conquer, tree traversal, and dynamic programming.", "key_points": ["Every recursive function must have a base case to stop.", "Each call is pushed onto the call stack; deep recursion can cause stack overflow.", "Time complexity depends on number of recursive calls × work per call.", "Can usually be replaced with an explicit stack for iterative equivalent.", "Used in DFS, tree traversal, Merge Sort, Quick Sort, and Fibonacci."], "code": {"c": "// Factorial using recursion
int factorial(int n) {
    if (n <= 1) return 1;  // base case
    return n * factorial(n - 1);
}

// Fibonacci
int fib(int n) {
    if (n <= 1) return n;
    return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);
}", "python": "def factorial(n):
    if n <= 1:     # base case
        return 1
    return n * factorial(n - 1)

def fib(n):
    if n <= 1:
        return n
    return fib(n - 1) + fib(n - 2)

print(factorial(5))  # 120
print(fib(6))        # 8", "cpp": "int factorial(int n) {
